<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06052i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06052i">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06052i"> 52(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> break doll</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est au m&ecirc;me d&eacute;sir de se rendre compte qu&apos;ob&eacute;issent les enfants quand ils &eacute;ventrent leurs polichinelles. &ldquo;A l&apos;aide de quels ressorts myst&eacute;rieux la paupi&egrave;re d&apos;une poup&eacute;e ferme les yeux, comment b&ecirc;le le mouton m&eacute;canique, par quel moyen roule le cheval, l&apos;enfant a soif de le savoir; c&apos;est pourquoi, depuis le commencement de l&apos;humanit&eacute;, il a toujours <mark>cass&eacute; ses jouets</mark>, enrichissant, sans s&apos;en douter, nos vitrines des mus&eacute;es antiques de petites <mark>poup&eacute;es</mark> d&apos;argile sans bras ni jambes&rdquo; <font color="green">[It is with the same desire to understand that inspire children when they disembowel their dolls. &ldquo;With the help of what mysterious springs the eyelid of a doll closes the eyes, how the mechanical sheep beats, by what means rolls the horse, the child is thirsty to know it; that is why, since the beginning of mankind, he has always broken his toys, enriching, without suspecting it, our antique museum windows with little clay dolls without arms or legs.&rdquo;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 106</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
